{{Infobox song contest entry | song = {{flagicon|Croatia}} "Don't Ever Cry" | image = | caption = | year = 1993 | country = Croatia | artist = Vivien Galletta, Olja Dešić, Melita Sedić, Naim Ajra, Petar Čučak, Anđela Jeličić | as = [[Put (band)|Put]] | with = | genre = | language = | languages = [[Croatian language|Croatian]], [[English language|English]] | composer = Andrej Baša | lyricist = Đorđe Novković | conductor = Andrej Baša | place = 15th | points = 31 | place_semi = | points_semi = | lyrics = [http://www.diggiloo.net/?1993hr Lyrics] | clip = | next = "Nek' ti bude ljubav sva" | next_link = Nek' ti bude ljubav sva }}
"'''Don't Ever Cry'''" was the [[Croatia]]n entry in the [[Eurovision Song Contest 1993]], performed partly in [[English Language|English]] and partly in [[Croatian Language|Croatian]] by [[Put (band)|Put]]. This was Croatia's debut as an independent nation in the [[Eurovision Song Contest]].
The song written by [[Đorđe Novković]] was performed twenty-first on the night (following the [[Netherlands]]'s [[Ruth Jacott]] with "[[Vrede (song)|Vrede]]" and preceding [[Spain]]'s [[Eva Santamaría]] with "[[Hombres (song)|Hombres]]"). At the close of voting, it had received 31 points, placing 15th in a field of 25.
The song is a plea for peace, set against the backdrop of the war of aggression which had recently engulfed Croatia. The song ends with the dramatic line "Don't ever cry, my Croatian sky".
It was succeeded as [[Croatia in the Eurovision Song Contest|Croatian representative]] at the [[Eurovision Song Contest 1994|1994 Contest]] by [[Tony Cetinski]] with "[[Nek' ti bude ljubav sva]]".
